%N A337249 Numbers k for which csc(k) > k.
%C A337249 a(14) > 1.129*10^12, if it exists. - _Kevin P. Thompson_, Nov 07 2021
%C A337249 a(14) exists. The numbers 428224593349304, 6134899525417045, 66627445592888887, 430010946591069243, and 2646693125139304345 all satisfy csc(k) > k and are larger than a(13). It is not yet proven whether these are a(14)-a(18) or if there are any other numbers in the sequence before or between them. - _Wolfe Padawer_, Apr 11 2023
%C A337249 a(14)-a(18) confirmed. - _Matt Frank_, Jun 05 2026
%C A337249 Proof that the Python code produces exactly the solutions to the inequalities csc(k) > k and 1 <= k <= K: Since k = 1 is initialized in the output, assume k >= 2. The final check on k's ensures that only solutions to the inequalities are output. Let m be the nearest integer to k/Pi. The condition csc(k) > k implies |k - m*Pi| < arcsin(1/k) and therefore k*|k - m*Pi| < 2. Now let k = t*p, m = t*q, where p/q is in lowest terms. Then t^2*p*|p - q*Pi| < 2, which is the limit on t's tested in the code. The bound also shows |k - m*Pi| < arcsin(1/k) < 1.1/k < 1/(2*m), so |Pi - k/m| < 1/(2*m^2). By Legendre's theorem, p/q must be a convergent of Pi, and p <= k <= K. So the code by testing all convergents with numerators up to K tests this combination of p and q, and outputs all solutions to the inequalities. - _Matt Frank_, Jul 16 2026
%e A337249 csc(1) = 1.1884... so 1 is a term.
%t A337249 Select[Range[10^6], Csc[#] > # &] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 21 2020 *)
%o A337249 (PARI) isok(m) = 1/sin(m) > m; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Aug 27 2020
%o A337249 (Python)
%o A337249 import mpmath as mp
%o A337249 digits = 24
%o A337249 K = 10 ** digits
%o A337249 mp.mp.dps = max(80, 4 * digits)
%o A337249 out = {1}
%o A337249 pold, qold = 0, 1
%o A337249 p, q = 1, 0
%o A337249 x = mp.pi
%o A337249 while p < K:
%o A337249     a = int(mp.floor(x))
%o A337249     pold, p = p, a * p + pold
%o A337249     qold, q = q, a * q + qold
%o A337249     err = p - q * mp.pi
%o A337249     tmax = mp.sqrt(2 / abs(p * err))
%o A337249     for t in range(1, int(tmax) + 1):
%o A337249         k = t * p
%o A337249         if 0 < k * mp.sin(k) < 1 and k < K:
%o A337249             out.add(k)
%o A337249     x = 1 / (x - a)
%o A337249 print(sorted(out))
%o A337249 # _Matt Frank_, Jul 16 2026
